The study history of Estonian and Finno-Ugric languages is introduced in the form of lectures and seminars. The first half of the course is dedicated to the study of Estonian, the second half to the study of other Finno-Ugric (Uralic) languages. The course include two independent homeworks that deepen knowledge on Estonian and Finno-Ugric linguistics. The course includes a visit to institutions that are related to studying, teaching or developing these languages.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The main objective of the course is to provide an overview of Estonian and other Finno-Ugric languages and linguistics, the main milestones and central persons in the study history of these languages and main directions of current linguistic studies in this field. In addition the course increases competences in finding and assessing relevant  information related to the topics of the course.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After completing the course students - know which languages and language groups belong to the Uralic language family. - know the main periods, milestones, researchers and relevant topics in the study of Uralic languages; - have deepened their knowledge on one language or relevant topic in the study history of Uralic languages; - know the main periods, milestones, researchers and relevant topics in the study of Estonian,  - have deepened their knowledge on one relevant topic in the study history of Estonian; - know the main centers in Estonia where Estonian and other Finno-Ugric are studied; - is able to find, assess and present relevant information related to the study of Estonian and Finno-Ugric languages.
